<dl id="n10079h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10079h">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10079h"> 79(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> battlefield <font color="green">[bones]</font> bartered / hand out of soil / boars eat</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Unburied Dead</b> &hellip; Human <mark>Bones Bartered by Battlefield Ghouls</mark> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The still undisturbed battle-grounds of Verdun and the Meuse furnish a profitable livelihood to ghouls, who take bones from the shell-churned soil and find a market for them.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Bones by the Handful To this an English visitor to France can testify from his own experience. During the Easter holiday he went to stay with a French friend who resides in the Varennes, and together they wandered over the outskirts of what was once the Argonne forest <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Here, in the dusty chalky <mark>soil, human finger bones can be gathered by the handful</mark>, and the remains of soldiers hastily buried on the battlefield and since <mark>unearthed by wild boars foraging for food</mark> can still be found. <small> <a name="FJ23apr24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FJ23apr24"><cite title="source">Freeman's Journal</cite></a> (23 April 1924) 5/6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
